The orientation of the zygopophyseal joints varies in different regions of the spinal column and thereby influences the range of movement between adjacent vertebrae around the three possible axes.
Fig. 14: The orientation of zygapophyseal joints
This orientation allows movement along all three possible axis, permitting flexion and extension, lateral flexion, and rotation of the cervical spine.
This orientation allows movement primarily along two axes, permitting  lateral flexion and rotation of the thoracic spine.
This orientation allows movement primarily along one axis, permitting  flexion and extension of the lumbar spine.
